  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Post-operative pain following total knee replacement can be disabling and sometimes lead to
      the need for prolonged hospital stay. Therefore development of improved post-operative
      modalities for total knee replacement surgery pain control is important. High-resolution
      ultrasound (US) allows accurate visualization of nerves and surrounding structures and can
      lead to higher success rates of nerve block. The investigators aim at comparing the analgesic
      efficacy of ultrasound-guided nerve block catheter compared with epidural analgesia for
      patients with knee OA who underwent unilateral total knee replacement.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
